;; appendix-j-poetry-prose-playable.book.slatl

(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(appendix
  :book                "Book of Narrative Games"
  :letter              "J"
  :title               "Poetry, Prose, and Playable Text"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :G
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :prose
"When text arrives, HOW it arrives is half the meaning. A prose block
that pops onto the screen reads flat. The same block that eases in
over three seconds reads considered. The same block that drops from
above, letter-by-letter, reads like a poem being written in front of
you.

This appendix is a decision guide. When to use which text-motion
verb. Which combinations feel right for which content. What NOT to
do (many things).

---

## The three arrival verbs

**motion/drop** — text falls from above and settles into place.

```scheme
(paint-text 40 60 \"The kitchen at dawn.\")
(motion/drop 'text-slot :duration 45 :ease 'ease-out)
```

Feel: gentle, considered, like a leaf falling. Best for prose that
should feel like a thought arriving.

**motion/with-feel** — text arrives with a specific emotional
signature (a shape of motion).

```scheme
(paint-text 40 60 \"You do not know when they will come back.\")
(motion/with-feel 'text-slot 'tender)
```

Feel: parametric. `'tender` is soft ease. `'urgent` is fast slam.
`'reluctant` is slow drag. Different feels for different tones.

**motion/with-pace** — text unfolds character-by-character at a
controllable speed.

```scheme
(motion/with-pace \"You do not know when they will come back.\"
                  40 60 :chars-per-sec 12)
```

Feel: someone typing the text in real time. Slow (5 chars/sec) reads
as thoughtful; fast (30 chars/sec) reads as breathless.

---

## Choosing between them

For prose passages that feel like paragraphs from a book:
`motion/drop` per line.

For lines that carry specific emotional weight (a confession, a
farewell): `motion/with-feel` with a matching feel.

For lines that should feel like they are being SPOKEN or WRITTEN in
the moment (a voice message, a note being read aloud):
`motion/with-pace`.

For lines with no special weight: plain `paint-text` with no
animation.

You can mix them within a scene. The variation itself is meaningful.

---

## Pace as gameplay

Player controls pace by pressing a key between lines.

```scheme
(define (player-paced-poem lines)
  (let ((idx 0))
    (define (show-line)
      (when (< idx (length lines))
        (let ((line (list-ref lines idx))
              (y (+ 40 (* idx 60))))
          (paint-text 40 y line)
          (motion/drop 'text-slot :duration 45)
          (set! idx (+ idx 1)))))
    (show-line)   ;; first line automatic
    (on-key
      (lambda (k)
        (when (eq? k 'space) (show-line))))))
```

Player presses SPACE. The next line drops in. They wait however long
they want.

This is the essential structure of a playable poem. The reader is
also the pacer. Poems that would be over in twelve seconds if
autoplay-ed become three-minute meditations under the reader's
control.

---

## Auto-advance with the option to skip

For hybrid experiences — prose that mostly self-plays but can be
skipped or paused.

```scheme
(define (auto-advance-with-skip lines)
  (let ((idx 0) (paused? #f))
    (define (show-line)
      (when (and (< idx (length lines)) (not paused?))
        (let ((line (list-ref lines idx)))
          (paint-text 40 (+ 40 (* idx 60)) line)
          (motion/drop 'text-slot :duration 45)
          (set! idx (+ idx 1))
          (world/after 150 show-line))))
    (show-line)
    (on-key
      (lambda (k)
        (case k
          ((space)
           (set! paused? (not paused?))
           (unless paused? (show-line)))
          ((right)
           (show-line)))))))
```

Auto-advances every 2.5 seconds. SPACE pauses/unpauses. RIGHT
advances immediately. The player who wants to speed up can; the
player who wants to slow down can.

---

## Lines that linger vs lines that fade

Some lines should stay on screen for the whole scene. Some should
fade after being read.

```scheme
(define (mixed-behavior-poem)
  ;; Line 1 stays.
  (paint-text 40 60 \"The kitchen at dawn.\")
  (motion/drop 'line-1 :duration 45)

  ;; Line 2 fades after 90 frames.
  (world/after 100
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 40 110 \"A jar of honey with a spoon in it.\")
      (motion/drop 'line-2 :duration 45)
      (world/after 90
        (lambda () (surface/dim 0.0 60)))))    ;; fade

  ;; Line 3 stays.
  (world/after 250
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 40 160 \"Someone was here.\")
      (motion/drop 'line-3 :duration 45)))
  )
```

Fading lines are ones the reader should HOLD IN THEIR MIND while
reading the next. The honey line fades as 'someone was here'
arrives — the reader connects them mentally.

Do not fade every other line. Choose specific ones.

---

## Spotlight on one word

The equivalent of italic emphasis in prose.

```scheme
(paint-text 40 60 \"You do not know when they will come back.\")
;; Spotlight the word 'when.'
(world/after 60
  (lambda ()
    (surface/spotlight 145 60 30 20 :duration 90)))
```

'When' becomes the emotional center. The reader's eye goes there. In
prose you would italicize it; in playable text you spotlight it.

Once or twice per poem. Not every line.

---

## Motion as meaning

Text can move AFTER arriving. Rain lines fall. Water lines settle.
Wind lines drift.

```scheme
;; A wind line drifts to the right slowly.
(paint-text 40 100 \"the wind through the reeds\")
(motion/move-to 'wind-line 200 100 :duration 300 :ease 'linear)
```

The line 'the wind through the reeds' physically drifts. The
audience feels the wind because the text does. This is what makes
playable poetry different from a printed page.

Use sparingly. If EVERY line moves, motion becomes background noise.
One or two moving lines per poem.

---

## Sound in poetry

Every poem should have exactly one audio element beyond silence.
Maybe an ambient. Maybe one cue on one line. Not both, usually.

```scheme
;; A poem with a single audio cue.
(paint-text 40 60 \"The stone drops.\")
(motion/drop 'line-1 :duration 45)
(audio/play 'stone-in-water :volume 0.4)

;; The rest of the poem is silent.
(world/after 90
  (lambda ()
    (paint-text 40 110 \"The ripples cross the whole face of it.\")
    (motion/drop 'line-2 :duration 45)))
```

One sound cue on one line. The stone drop is heard exactly when the
line arrives. The rest is silence, which lets the reader hear their
own breathing.

If you use ambient, use ONE ambient layer at very low volume
(0.1-0.15). Poetry does not need three layers.

---

## The blank space rule

Playable poems benefit from empty screen space around the text.

```scheme
;; Wide margins.
(paint-text 200 200 \"one small line, centered\")
```

Position the text with wide margins. The white (or paper-colored)
space around the words gives them weight. This is the same principle
as poetry books using large margins.

Cluttered pages read as prose. Sparse pages read as poetry. Choose
your positioning to match your intent.

---

## Combining forms — the prose-with-a-poem

Sometimes a narrative scene has a poetic moment inside it.

```scheme
(define (scene-with-poetic-moment)
  ;; Normal prose lines.
  (paint-text 20 40 \"You climb the hill. You reach the top.\")
  (paint-text 20 70 \"You look at the valley below.\")

  ;; Then a poetic beat.
  (world/after 150
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 40 150 \"The wind.\")
      (motion/drop 'poetic-1 :duration 60 :ease 'ease-out)))

  (world/after 280
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 40 200 \"The hawk.\")
      (motion/drop 'poetic-2 :duration 60 :ease 'ease-out)))

  (world/after 410
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 40 250 \"The distance you did not know you could see.\")
      (motion/drop 'poetic-3 :duration 60 :ease 'ease-out)))

  ;; Then back to prose.
  (world/after 570
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 20 340 \"You breathe out. You start down.\"))))
```

Normal prose. Then three poetic lines with `motion/drop` and wider
margins. Then normal prose again. The scene has a poem inside it.

This is a great technique for high-emotional beats in an otherwise
prose-heavy game. The shift in TEXTURE tells the reader 'this is
important.'

---

## What NOT to do

**Don't animate every line.** If every line has motion, motion loses
meaning. Reserve motion for lines that need weight.

**Don't use character-by-character pace for prose paragraphs.**
Typewriter-style unfolding is a specific effect — for voice
messages, notes being read, direct messages from characters. It is
annoying for narrative prose.

**Don't spotlight everything.** One or two spotlights per scene.

**Don't run motion during choice text.** When the player is about to
pick a choice, the choice options should be still. Moving text is
harder to read.

**Don't autoplay through emotional beats.** Give the player a moment
to sit with a line before advancing. Even 1-2 seconds of pause
between an emotional line and the next line matters.

---

## Timing reference

For prose:
- 200-300ms per line of arrival animation
- 3-5 seconds of hold before next line

For poetry:
- 500-800ms per line of arrival animation (slower is more considered)
- 5-10 seconds of hold before next line — or player-paced

For dialogue:
- 100-200ms of arrival (fast, feels like speaking)
- Advance on player key press

Tune for your content. Rules of thumb, not laws.

---

## Summary

Three arrival verbs (drop, with-feel, with-pace). Player-paced or
auto-advance. Lines linger or fade. Spotlight for emphasis. Motion
for meaning. Sound sparingly. Blank space matters. Combine forms
for poetic beats inside prose scenes.

The kid who reads this appendix and then reads a paper poem will
suddenly notice how the poet used LINE BREAKS as motion. Playable
text just makes the motion explicit.")
